ullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:869,&quot;width&quot;:999,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:189297,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F26f73617-4fc7-4d55-94ac-9ec4b01edd92_999x869.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F26f73617-4fc7-4d55-94ac-9ec4b01edd92_999x869.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F26f73617-4fc7-4d55-94ac-9ec4b01edd92_999x869.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F26f73617-4fc7-4d55-94ac-9ec4b01edd92_999x869.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption"><em>Image Credit-Midjourney</em></figcaption></figure></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/p/you-must-master-the-art-of-unproductivity?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/p/you-must-master-the-art-of-unproductivity?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p><p>The productivity cult is about to die.</p><p>Finally. Many of us have been praying to a fake god for this moment in history. It‚Äôs here. Happy dance. Yay.</p><p>In the old economy, it was all about productivity.</p><ul><li><p>Hustle hard and work long hours</p></li><li><p>Use productivity apps</p></li><li><p>Attend lots of meetings</p></li><li><p>Consume endless amounts of information</p></li></ul><p>What‚Äôs changed is AI can now do hard work and meaningless admin at scale. Every day that passes, AI can do more of humans' bullsh*t work.</p><p>Fast forward two more years and humans won‚Äôt need to do many of the hard work activities we once did. It‚Äôs going to leave a strange void in the world. For once in humanity‚Äôs existence we‚Äôll have a lot less to do.</p><p>Before you get excited, it doesn‚Äôt mean we‚Äôll all be sitting on mobile recliners watching Netflix all day, as the animated movie Walle-E suggested. No.</p><p>What it means is productivity will no longer f*cking matter.</p><p>What will now matter is creativity.</p><p>Music, art, acting, painting, solving hard problems‚Ä¶. will go back to being the dominant forces that shape the world, the way they did during the Renaissance period hundreds of years ago.</p><p>To prepare for this creative revolution, you‚Äôll need to master the art of unproductivity. Unlike productive habits, the ones that help you be more creative are uns*xy as hell.</p><p>Here are the new habits you‚Äôll need to master.</p><h1>Walk like Socrates through nature as if it‚Äôs 350 BC</h1><p>The modern workday sucks because it doesn‚Äôt include walking.</p><p>You wake up in a box. Eat from a box. Commute in a box to an office cubicle. And maybe drink a cylinder of Coke for lunch to change things up.</p><p>When I started working for myself one thing that changed is I began to walk like a madman. I‚Äôd often turn meetings into walking meetings. I found not only did I feel better, but I was more creative. Walking in nature takes it a step further.</p><p>The greenery and fresh air help the mind unwind.</p><p>Dan Koe once said:</p><blockquote><p><em>‚ÄúAncient Romans and Greeks, Steve Jobs, Charles Darwin, and an ever-growing list of visionaries, strategists, and innovators attribute their success to surprisingly low work times accompanied by an abundance of restful activities like long walks.‚Äù</em></p></blockquote><p>The greats from the past didn‚Äôt work long hours, and going forward we won‚Äôt need to either. Walks are a perfect way to fill in the extra time, so when we are working we‚Äôre 10x more creative.</p><p>One thing that makes my walks more interesting is imagining that someone from 1000s of years ago walked the same steps that I‚Äôm walking right now. It lights a bonfire underneath my imagination and helps me come alive. Try it.</p><p>To unlock your creative superpower make sure to throw your headphones in a lake and walk in silence.</p><div class="pullquote"><p>I‚Äôm not saying going for a walk will solve all your problems, I‚Äôm just saying there‚Äôs no problem that‚Äôs going to be made worse by going for a walk ‚Äì Ryan Holiday</p></div><h1>Daydream in the middle of the day</h1><p>I once sat in the lobby of the bank I worked at daydreaming.</p><p>The next day my boss told me that a ‚ÄúHead of‚Äù thought I was slacking off and not talking to enough customers. What that dumbass didn‚Äôt realize is, while daydreaming, I thought of a way to onboard more tech companies to our bank using a referral partner.</p><p>This breakthrough would never have happened if I spent 12 hours a day only talking to customers and yelling ‚Äúbuy our bank accounts, sir, they‚Äôre the best. We‚Äôll make you rich.‚Äù</p><p><strong>New mental model:</strong></p><pre><code>If you learned something at work, it‚Äôs probably time to forget it or at least relearn it.</code></pre><p>There‚Äôs some sh*tty programming the corporate world infects you with ‚Äì not being able to daydream is one example.</p><p>Another way to daydream is to go watch traffic on a freeway for 3 hours. The movement of the cars becomes like a free form of meditation. When we daydream we activate our imagination and escape the hell of our to-do list.</p><p>I find spending time with my 1 year old daughter helps too.</p><p>We‚Äôre always imagining new games to play, and pretending regular household items are strange characters. The other day my daughter told me the broom was actually a horse that escaped from the enchanted forest. I‚Äôll roll with that. Sounds plausible. The brush does kind of look like a horse‚Äôs mane if you think about it.</p><p>What turns an adult back into a baby is a lack of imagination.</p><p>(It‚Äôs the new pandem!c, by the way.)</p><p>You‚Äôre gonna need that old rusty imagination again if you want to survive the AI wars and still make money in this new economy. Start turning brooms into wild horses.</p><div class="pullquote"><p>The creativity part doesn‚Äôt happen without the daydreaming. In my line of work, I need to daydream ‚Äì Lin-Manuel (creator of the Hamilton Musical)</p></div><h1>Write like Hemingway is your hero</h1><p>I shouldn‚Äôt admit this (and don‚Äôt tell my wife) but writing makes me h0rny.</p><p>Not in a s*xual way, but in a way where writing forces my brain to come alive and join the dots between ideas.</p><pre><code>I find I have ideas while I write ‚Äì not the other way around.</code></pre><p>Writing is one of the best ways to be creative. Every artistic outlet can begin with writing.</p><ul><li><p>A movie starts as writing.</p></li><li><p>A painting starts as words on a page.</p></li><li><p>A podcast starts with an email pitch to a guest.</p></li><li><p>A Youtube video starts as a written script (yes, Youtube is mostly all scripted).</p></li></ul><p>Your life will get better if you write every day. The next level is to write and publish on social media. This allows your ideas to become magnets for opportunities and humans that can elevate those ideas beyond your inner world.</p><p>Groups gathering for the purpose of creativity are going to be crucial in the new economy. Let writing help you form the network needed.</p><div class="pullquote"><p>If you‚Äôre thinking without writing, you only think you‚Äôre thinking ‚Äî Leslie Lamport</p></div><h1>Blow your ear drums out with this type of music</h1><p>Modern music sucks.</p><p>I used to be a DJ for 10 years. The rock of the 70s and 80s, or the pop of the 90s, or the house/dance music of the early 2000s is way better than the boring sh*t we have now from artists like Kendrik Lemar.</p><p>They put these stupid filters on their voice that make them sound like robots. I prefer to just listen to a human voice without all the robot sounds.</p><p>I‚Äôve been thinking about music a lot lately.</p><ul><li><p>Is it that we‚Äôve written every chord progression or melody in existence already and that‚Äôs why modern music sucks?</p></li><li><p>Is the technology making the music sound worse?</p></li><li><p>Is music not as exciting anymore in a dopamine-fuelled world where you can get bigger rushes of adrenaline from video games or p*rn?</p></li></ul><p>I‚Äôve concluded it‚Äôs none of that. Music sucks because creativity is lacking.</p><p>We‚Äôre so busy working to cover the high cost of living that there‚Äôs not a lot of spare time to be creative.</p><p>Between news, politics, and social media our brains are fried. We‚Äôre trained to think the world is worse than it is, so after a while we don‚Äôt have the energy or optimism to sit down at a piano and make a beautiful piece of music inspired by a love affair.</p><p>We don‚Äôt even have as many love affairs anymore because going to a bar for a drink isn‚Äôt as convenient as texting a Tinder buddy (who soon, too, will be an AI bot). Why find love when you can make love to a s*x doll? Sounds odd, but that's where we‚Äôre heading.</p><p>The quality of music is a reflection of the quality of human consciousness.</p><p>We‚Äôre at rock bottom, especially right before the US election, but thankfully we‚Äôre on the cusp of good times and great classic hits again as creativity takes center stage once more.</p><p>To make better music and be more creative we still need music, though. I recommend movie soundtracks. Turn on a bit of Hans Zimmer during the day and watch it change your mood. You‚Äôll feel inspired to create.</p><div class="pullquote"><p>If you listen to songs on your phone sorted by when you added them, you are essentially going back in time. Songs trigger memories, wonderfully so! ‚Äì Ankur Warikoo</p></div><h1>Read and feel like you‚Äôre taking speed</h1><p>The gurus on Twitter/X say reading is procrastination in disguise.</p><p>They say you need to have a goal in mind before you read any book, like everything is a f*cking self-help concert starring Tony Robbins on lead guitar, Jim Rohn on the drums, and Zig Ziglar rapping. Screw those illiterate morons on X.</p><p>Reading is incredible. </p><p>On the surface it‚Äôs unproductive. Below the surface it‚Äôs the source of better ideas and an expanded vocabulary.</p><p>When your vocabulary expands you get better at explaining things. You become more articulate which makes you a better communicator. In a world of AI, you better hope your human communication skills are first-class.</p><p>The best way to choose a book to read is to follow your curiosity.</p><p>I double dare you to piss off the productivity gurus and read a fiction book. That‚Äôll really get ‚Äòem raging and seeing red! (haha evil Denning)</p><div class="pullquote"><p>To experience time travel, read. To achieve immortality, write ‚Äì James Clear</p></div><h1>Practice forced solitude while smoking a fat corn cob pipe</h1><p>Loners are the new elites.</p><p>Being unproductive often means being alone. The need to be around others all the time is often why people work office jobs. They can‚Äôt stand not to have office friends. I don‚Äôt say this as an insult. Nope.</p><p>I worked in banking for 10 years longer than I should because I was lonely.</p><p>Seeing Greg the concierge or Amelia the cleaner was the highlight of my day. We‚Äôd talk smack about lots of stuff, even topics I had no clue about (like AFL football).</p><p>Disappearing to a wood cabin in a forest and smoking a corn cob pipe used to be the dream. Then people laughed at it. In this creative boom, it‚Äôs going to become the goal again.</p><p>Suburban life has downsides. Where I live it‚Äôs a chorus of dogs barking 24/7. I may be home alone as I write this, but it feels like I‚Äôve got 101 Dalmatians sitting next to me.</p><p>Without true solitude it‚Äôs hard to think deeply. It‚Äôs hard to uncover those big ideas we have stuck inside our s*xy brains. Start escaping to the woods now as a habit, so you can develop this skill in time for the creative boom.</p><div class="pullquote"><p>It takes 4-6 weeks of uncomfortable isolation to create a new vision for yourself, and your life ‚Äì Zach Pogrob</p></div><h1>Be quieter than normal</h1><p>The productivity age loves talking.</p><p>Go into a productive workplace and you‚Äôll see endless meetings full of people talking over the top of each other. People just keep talking because they want to feel like they‚Äôre #AddingValue or coming across as smart to their colleagues.</p><p>True creative people are quieter than two ants having s*x.</p><p>Record producer Rick Rubin is one such example. The dude has a long beard and is famous for being quiet in front of the world‚Äôs biggest musicians. Or take actor Keanu Reeves (who I‚Äôm convinced is Jesus reincarnated).</p><p>The guy does these big-ass interviews and spends much of the time taking long pauses and looking up at the ceiling. I‚Äôve found quiet people have smaller egos. This makes them more creative because our ego often stands in the way of our best ideas.</p><p>Listen more than you talk. Try saying nothing for the next 24 hours.</p><blockquote><p>Quiet people have the loudest minds ‚Äì Stephen Hawking</p></blockquote><h1>Final Thought</h1><p>The mind is your biggest asset. Without taking care of it, you‚Äôll never be creative enough to thrive in the digital renaissance of the 2020s.</p><p>Get used to feeling like you‚Äôre pissing your time down the toilet. Being unproductive is how you‚Äôll increase your creativity, so you can outperform AI and carve a path in life that‚Äôll lead you to personal freedom.</p><p>Tell me which of these unproductive ideas you loved the most and why in the comments.</p><div><hr></div><p>P.S. Are you writing online?&nbsp;</p><p>If so, how's it going?&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://forms.gle/52b4ZFkQCDLXdfQF7">Take my gut-check survey here.</a></p></body></html>	Productivity cult fades as AI takes over mundane tasks. Creativity becomes key. Embrace unproductivity: walk in nature, daydream, write daily, listen to inspiring music, read widely, seek solitude, and practice quietness.	2024-09-26 11:04:39	2024-10-05 19:39:39.567	2024-10-10 14:04:45.042	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F26f73617-4fc7-4d55-94ac-9ec4b01edd92_999x869.jpeg	Tim Denning	you-must-master-the-art-of-unproductivity-if-you-want-to-be-successful-in-the-new-economy
