173	https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases	The "warming surge," climate model biases, fewer Gulf hurricanes, and super shoes! 	Some really interesting new peer-reviewed papers	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png" width="412" height="412" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:720,&quot;width&quot;:720,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:412,&quot;bytes&quot;:1389742,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">Separating wheat from chaff</figcaption></figure></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><p>In 2024 it can be difficult to sort wheat from chaff in the peer-reviewed literature. There has always been better and worse science ‚Äî that goes with the territory ‚Äî but as I argued last week, we are now in <a href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/weaponizing-peer-review">an era of tactical research</a>, with science curated to advance narratives over knowledge. That makes knowing what‚Äôs what even more difficult.</p><p>I spend a lot of time here at THB on the chaff, and by reader request, I am going to try to spend more time also on the wheat. To that end, this week has already seen cross my desk an unusually large number of really interesting recent peer-reviewed papers that I‚Äôm sharing with you today. Let‚Äôs get to it . . .</p><ul><li><p><strong>A recent surge in global warming is not detectable yet</strong> (<a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s43247-024-01711-1">Beaulieu et al. 2024</a>, open access). Top line results: </p><blockquote><p>‚ÄúOur results show limited evidence for a warming surge; in most surface temperature time series, no change in the warming rate beyond the 1970s is detected despite the breaking record temperatures observed in 2023.‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>The paper employs the traditional IPCC framework for detection and attribution and assess what levels of global temperature increases would have to occur to achieve detection. The authors find that the recent ‚Äúsurge‚Äù is not very close to that magnitude of increase:</p><blockquote><p>‚ÄúAccounting for the short-term variability in the HadCRUT GMST over 1970‚Äì2023 and the added uncertainty for the changepoint location, the second segment (2013‚Äì2023) would need a slope of at least 0.039‚àòC/year (more than a 100% increase) to be statistically different than 0.019 at the Œ±‚Äâ=‚Äâ0.05 significance level right now. The estimated slope of 0.029‚Äâ‚àòC/year falls far short of this needed increase. While it is still possible there was a change in the warming rate starting in 2013, the HadCRUT record is simply not long enough for the surge to be statistically detectable at this time.‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>This paper is sure to motivate much debate as it is contrary to gobsmacking claims made by some visible scientists. Debate is good for science and for science in the public eye.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p></li><li><p><strong>Crucial role of sea surface temperature warming patterns in near-term high-impact weather and climate projection</strong> (<a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41612-024-00681-7">Zhao and Knutson 2024</a>, open access). <a href="https://www.gfdl.noaa.gov/research_highlight/crucial-role-of-sea-surface-temperature-warming-patterns-in-near-term-high-impact-weather-and-climate-projection/">Top line results</a>:</p><blockquote><ul><li><p>‚ÄúModel biases in SST [sea surface temperature] trend patterns are shown to have profound implications for near-term projections of high-impact storm statistics, including the frequency of atmospheric rivers, tropical storms and mesoscale convection systems, as well as for hydrological and climate sensitivity. If the future SST warming pattern continues to resemble the observed pattern from the past few decades rather than the model-simulated/predicted patterns, these results suggest:</p><ul><li><p>A drastically different future projection of high-impact storms and their associated hydroclimate changes, especially over the Western Hemisphere.</p></li><li><p>Stronger global hydrological sensitivity.</p></li><li><p>Substantially less global warming due to stronger negative feedback and lower climate sensitivity.‚Äù</p></li></ul></li></ul></blockquote><p>This paper identifies systematic biases in how climate models represent ocean temperatures and explores the implications of these biases for projections of the climate future. The paper concludes:</p><blockquote><p>‚ÄúOur results indicate that if the future SST trend pattern continues to resemble the observed pattern from the past few decades rather than that simulated or predicted by climate models, we would anticipate a drastically different picture of future changes of high-impact storm statistics . . .‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>This paper as well will likely motivate some interesting discussions and future work. The most important implication for consumers of climate research is to recognize that our near-term climate future likely encompasses a much wider range of possibilities than we (collectively) generally expect or hear discussed.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p></li><li><p><strong>Robust future projections of global spatial distribution of major tropical cyclones and sea level pressure gradients</strong> (<a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s43247-024-01644-9">Murakami et al. 2024</a>, open access).</p><p></p><p>I found this paper particularly interesting because it was published just a few weeks before Hurricanes Helene and Milton made landfall on the U.S. Gulf Coast, killing hundreds and resulting in tens of billions of dollars in economic losses. As you can see in the figure below this new paper projects a significant decrease (blue shading) in the strongest hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png" width="610" height="323.3" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:477,&quot;width&quot;:900,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:610,&quot;bytes&quot;:404279,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3107b81-59c9-4f02-8895-84eb8cef9f9c_900x477.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><p>I share this paper not because I believe its projections over other studies ‚Äî actually, tell me what result you want for projected future hurricane incidence and I can produce a peer-reviewed study to support that view! ‚Äî but because it is at odds with major media reporting and claims by activists (including some scientists) about trends and projections in hurricanes. The gap between popular climate discourse and peer reviewed research (including the assessments of the IPCC WG1) remains massive. This paper offers another timely example.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p></li><li><p><strong>Can the recent sex-specific evolutions in elite running performances be attributed to advanced footwear technology?</strong> (<a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/sports-and-active-living/articles/10.3389/fspor.2024.1386627/full">Mason et al. 2024</a>, open access)</p><p>This is a fun and interesting paper, which seeks to understand why elite women runners are running so much faster. The gains made by female runners using so-called ‚Äúsuper-shoe‚Äù technology are much greater than gains made by elite men. The paper argues that understanding this issue lacks evidence because most studies are of men, and neglect women. The authors explore,</p><blockquote><p>‚Äúwhy women may be benefiting from the new generation of shoes more than men, suggest potential mechanisms leading to hypotheses that need to be further investigated in upcoming studies, and finally propose that factors outside of footwear innovation may have concurrently driven the recently observed performance evolutions.‚Äù</p></blockquote><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases/comments&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Leave a comment&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases/comments"><span>Leave a comment</span></a></p><p><em>I welcome your comments and discussion. What papers crossed your desk that THB readers should know about? Tell us in the comments. THB is reader supported, which means I work for you. Please consider supporting!</em></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p></li></ul></body></html>	Recent peer-reviewed papers show limited evidence for a warming surge, systematic biases in climate models, and sex-specific evolutions in elite running performances.	2024-10-15 14:09:38	2024-10-16 14:49:02.057	2024-10-16 14:52:53.735	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F37affec7-72bb-4e61-b434-affc9026fe9c_720x720.png	Roger Pielke Jr.	the-warming-surge-climate-model-biases-fewer-gulf-hurricanes-and-super-shoes
171	https://thegeneralist.substack.com/p/how-vcs-build-soft-power	How VCs Build Soft Power	A guide to constructing a personal monopoly.	<html><head></head><body><p><em>üåü Hey there! This is a <strong>subscriber-only edition of our premium newsletter</strong> designed to make you a better investor, founder, and technologist. Members get access to the strategies, tactics, and wisdom of exceptional investors and founders. <a href="https://thegeneralist.substack.com/subscribe">Become a member today.</a></em></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://thegeneralist.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://thegeneralist.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg" width="1456" height="1133" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/eeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1133,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:3905277,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">Illustration by Harol Bustos</figcaption></figure></div><p>Friends,</p><p>In the land of venture capital, not all dollars are created equally. Though every bill possesses the same lineny texture, coveted color, and sensitive etching, each is bestowed with a distinctive gravity originating from its giver. Which is to say that receiving a $10 million investment from Founders Fund differs from receiving the same sum from an unheralded firm.&nbsp;</p><p>That entrepreneurs and the wider ecosystem feel this shimmering variance is a testament to soft power‚Äôs role in matching talent and capital. Even the industry‚Äôs best-resourced shops rely on voice, reach, reputation, influence, and storytelling to attract opportunities and outmaneuver rivals. In many cases, it is a fund‚Äôs principal weapon. If you were to strip Andreessen Horowitz of its platform team or Sequoia Capital of its senior talent, each would find a way to win, such is the strength of their soft power.</p><p>Soft power‚Äôs potency is matched only by the torpor with which it develops. It may take decades to burnish a reputation into a high sheen or chisel out a zone of influence, but it doesn‚Äôt have to. By developing a distinctive voice, leveraging the distributive reach of the Internet, and publishing differentiated work, even VCs in their first acts have been able to contrive a special magnetism, to draw boundaries around the beginnings of a personal monopoly.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>To understand how different managers construct soft power, we interviewed 17 notable investors. Some have been running firms and writing in public for over 20 years. Others are newer capital allocators but have already succeeded in standing out from the crowd, leveraging modern mediums and strategies. By learning about their approaches ‚Äì including the trade-offs made and lessons learned ‚Äì you‚Äôll be ready to accelerate your soft power campaign.&nbsp;</p><p>Although today‚Äôs guide is geared toward investors, its lessons are applicable to anyone interested in developing unique personal magnetism at scale.&nbsp;</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png" width="1080" height="1080" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1080,&quot;width&quot;:1080,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:472147,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F585fee07-25ac-407b-a84b-fe4c9b923b88_1080x1080.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><h2>What to expect</h2><ol><li><p><strong>Master how to build and leverage soft power</strong>. We created an 11,000-word guide on architecting a personal brand and making it work for you. It features details and insights you won‚Äôt find elsewhere.</p></li><li><p><strong>Learn from VCs who have done it</strong>. We compiled this guide by interviewing 17 VCs with soft power running differentiated strategies. The advice included is informed by practitioners in the arena, and the lessons they‚Äôve learned.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p><strong>Avoid common mistakes</strong>. In addition to our research, the VCs we‚Äôve interviewed have pointed out their mistakes and what they wished they‚Äôd done differently. We‚Äôve highlighted common pitfalls to ensure you side-step them and reap soft power‚Äôs rewards with less stress.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p><strong>Understand how to pick a content strategy</strong>. There is no right way to build soft power. Rather, you must choose a medium and a strategy leveraging your unique strengths. We walk through the trade-offs and help you navigate the idea maze faster.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p><strong>Hear how </strong><em><strong>exactly</strong></em><strong> investors benefit from soft power</strong>. Soft power is an intangible magic. Because of that, it can be difficult to understand its advantages. We dig into its benefits and explain why it‚Äôs well worth cultivating.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p></li></ol><p>This guide is the result of months of interviewing and research. It is designed to deliver Silicon Valley‚Äôs practitioners‚Äô best advice and strategies in a single edition.&nbsp;</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://thegeneralist.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://thegeneralist.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><div><hr></div><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png" width="315" height="109.20647149460709" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:225,&quot;width&quot;:649,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:315,&quot;bytes&quot;:9803,&quot;alt&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" title="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F292b3953-5cbc-4fed-9c75-2edcc8a13761_649x225.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div></div></div></a></figure></div><h3>Brought to you by Mercury</h3><p><strong>If Jony Ive built a banking* experience‚Ä¶</strong></p><p>I think it would look a lot like Mercury. The Generalist has been a Mercury customer for years, and I‚Äôm constantly awed by the platform‚Äôs beauty, thoughtfulness, and power. It‚Äôs become a core part of how we run our business and is probably the only banking product I find a genuine pleasure to use.&nbsp;</p><p>Mercury‚Äôs banking experience isn‚Äôt just loved by The Generalist. 200K other startups trust it to simplify their finances and power essential workflows, like paying bills or sending invoices. By using Mercury, customers save time, get granular visibility into their finances, and have finer-toothed control over money movement.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://mercury.com/?utm_source=the_generalist&amp;utm_medium=sponsored_newsletter&amp;utm_campaign=24q2_brand_campaign&amp;utm_content=homepage">Apply in minutes today at mercury.com to simplify your finances and perform at your best.</a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://mercury.com/?utm_source=the_generalist&amp;utm_medium=sponsored_newsletter&amp;utm_campaign=24q2_brand_campaign&amp;utm_content=homepage&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Learn more&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:&quot;button-wrapper&quot;}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary button-wrapper" href="https://mercury.com/?utm_source=the_generalist&amp;utm_medium=sponsored_newsletter&amp;utm_campaign=24q2_brand_campaign&amp;utm_content=homepage"><span>Learn more</span></a></p><p><em>*Mercury is a financial technology company, not a bank. Banking services provided by Choice Financial Group and Evolve Bank &amp; Trust¬Æ; Members FDIC.</em></p><div><hr></div><h2>Table of contents</h2><p><strong>1. Rules of thumb</strong></p><ul><li><p>Lower your shipping threshold</p></li><li><p>No tribute acts</p></li><li><p>Nothing too dear to kill</p></li><li><p>Fight the beige</p></li><li><p>Small is mighty</p></li><li><p>This is slow magic</p></li></ul><p><strong>2. Find the right medium</strong></p><ul><li><p>Writing</p></li><li><p>Podcasting</p></li><li><p>Social media</p></li><li><p>Other options</p></li></ul><p><strong>3. Find the right strategy</strong></p><ul><li><p>Selecting a strategy</p></li><li><p>Popularity vs. Influence</p></li><li><p>Consider the timing</p></li></ul><p><strong>4. The magic of soft power</strong></p><ul><li><p>Manufacturing serendipity</p></li><li><p>Build a network</p></li><li><p>Cultivate a prepared mind</p></li><li><p>Demonstrate your value</p></li></ul><p><em>Thank you to <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/tomasztunguz/">Tomasz Tunguz</a> (<a href="https://theory.ventures/">Theory</a>), <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/frank-rotman/">Frank Rotman</a> (<a href="https://www.qedinvestors.com/">QED</a>), <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/michaelhdempsey/">Michael Dempsey</a> <a href="https://www.compound.vc/">(Compound)</a>, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/nikhilbt/">Nikhil Basu-Trivedi</a> <a href="https://www.footwork.vc/">(Footwork)</a>, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/niki-scevak-15856/?originalSubdomain=au">Niki Scevak</a> <a href="https://www.blackbird.vc/">(Blackbird)</a>, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/rexwoodbury/">Rex Woodbury</a> (<a href="https://www.daybreakventures.com/">Daybreak</a>), <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/sajithpai/">Sajith Pai</a> (<a href="http://www.blume.vc/">Blume</a>), <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/sarahxguo/">Sarah Guo</a> (<a href="https://www.conviction.com/">Conviction</a>), <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/sarahtavel/">Sarah Tavel</a> (<a href="https://www.benchmark.com/">Benchmark</a>), <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/amiura/">Ann Miura-Ko</a> <a href="http://www.floodgate.com/">(Floodgate)</a>, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/chudson/">Charles Hudson</a> <a href="https://precursorvc.com/">(Precursor Ventures)</a>, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/loganbartlett/">Logan Bartlett </a><a href="http://www.redpoint.com/">(Redpoint)</a>, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/z-weinberg/">Zoe Weinberg</a> <a href="https://www.buildexante.com/">(Ex/ante)</a>, <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ataussig/">Alex Taussig</a> <a href="https://lsvp.com/">(Lightspeed)</a></em>, <em><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/kylesamani/">Kyle Samani</a> <a href="https://multicoin.capital/">(Multicoin)</a> <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/nathanbenaich/">Nathan Benaich</a> <a href="https://www.airstreet.com/">(Air Street)</a>, and <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/mollymielke/">Molly Mielke</a> <a href="https://www.mothfund.com/">(Moth)</a> for sharing their insights for this issue of the Investors Guide series.</em></p><div><hr></div><h2>1. Rules of thumb</h2><p>Before learning how to generate soft power, understanding why it‚Äôs valuable in a venture context is worthwhile. For much of the asset class‚Äôs history, having a strong public presence wasn‚Äôt necessary, given the relative lack of competition. When Ann Miura-Ko and Mike Maples formed Floodgate, for example, little marketing was required:</p><h4><strong>Floodgate</strong></h4><blockquote><p>In 2008, you didn‚Äôt even have to have a sign on your door. That has evolved.</p><p><em>‚Äì Ann Miura-Ko</em></p></blockquote><p>As the asset class has grown, inviting greater and fiercer competition, the need to differentiate has increased, too. Critically, firms must do more than distinguish themselves ‚Äì they must <em>message</em> those distinctions memorably, at scale. It is no good to hold a unique perspective or run an unusual model if entrepreneurs don‚Äôt know about it.&nbsp;</p><p>Frank Rotman of QED and Logan Bartlett of Redpoint articulated the importance of differentiation in today‚Äôs venture market.&nbsp;</p><h4><strong>QED</strong></h4><blockquote><p>It was much easier when fintech was a very niche thing. When we started investing <strong>in 2008, only $1 billion was invested in fintech globally. At its peak, it hit $140 billion. </strong>Those two ecosystems are not the same, right? Being a big fish in a little pond is not that hard. When a founder was looking to raise, they just had to ask, ‚ÄúWho is active?‚Äù That, plus a few very public winners like SoFi and Credit Karma, helped us a lot initially.&nbsp;</p><p>One day, it occurred to me that <strong>we weren‚Äôt the only game in town anymore</strong>. It was going to be a lot easier for everyone to know who we were rather than us knowing who everyone was. Just being active was no longer enough. <strong>My strategy was: You have to have a voice.</strong></p><p><em>‚Äì Frank Rotman</em></p></blockquote><h4><strong>Redpoint</strong></h4><blockquote><p><strong>Differentiating is really, really hard</strong>. Once upon a time, you had to show up in a room with a founder and differentiate there. It allowed for more personality and the ability to earn trust over time rather than in a shorter, more finite, transactional period.&nbsp;</p><p>During COVID, I realized that space was no longer a bottleneck. Anyone could be on a Zoom screen. I was competing with people like Marc Andreessen, who started the web browser; or Roelof Botha and Doug Leone, who were parachuting into deals; or someone like Keith Rabois. And <strong>I didn‚Äôt know what to do, honestly.</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>I started to think about finding a potentially additive way of getting myself out there. <strong>I knew I needed to stand out somehow</strong>, but I didn‚Äôt know what form it would take. It ultimately required a few cycles to figure it out.&nbsp;</p><p><em>‚Äì Logan Bartlett</em></p></blockquote><p>Creating that differentiation does not come easily. Many find it daunting to start ‚Äúthinking in public,‚Äù either through writing, podcasts, or another medium. A few rules of thumb can help overcome initial nerves, find your unique voice, avoid blandness, and initiate the alchemical process. I wish I had known these before starting <em>The Generalist</em>, and as it happens, much of the advice VCs gave echoed it.&nbsp;</p><ol><li><p>Lower your shipping threshold to start.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>No tribute acts.</p></li><li><p>Nothing too dear to kill.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>Fight the beige.</p></li><li><p>Small is mighty.</p></li><li><p>This is slow magic.&nbsp;</p></li></ol><h3>Lower your shipping threshold to start</h3><p>There will always be a good reason <em>not </em>to write an article or record a podcast. It takes time, focus, possibly social or financial capital, and a degree of vulnerability. What if you say something stupid? What if an investor you admire disagrees with your fundamental premise? In the short term, there seems to be much more to lose than gain.&nbsp;</p><p>Because of that, lowering your shipping threshold in the early days can be helpful. If you try to create something utterly perfect out of the gate ‚Äì especially if creating is new to you ‚Äì you‚Äôll likely stall out. A folder full of half-completed, unpublished blog posts is a sign that you‚Äôre stuck in this pattern. When you notice you‚Äôre falling into this kind of a cycle, narrow the scope of your project, lower your threshold for publishing, and get something out the door. As Steve Jobs <a href="https://www.folklore.org/Pirate_Flag.html?sort=date?sort=date">told</a> the Macintosh team in 1983: ‚ÄúReal artists ship.‚Äù</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg" width="688" height="529.1047619047619" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:323,&quot;width&quot;:420,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:688,&quot;bytes&quot;:13675,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F19057fc5-b6d9-40d4-a5eb-b77fe253eba8_420x323.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">The Macintosh team in front of the famous pirate flag (Folklore)</figcaption></figure></div><p>Sarah Guo is the founder of Conviction and the popular AI podcast <em><a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/no-priors-artificial-intelligence-technology-startups/id1668002688">No Priors</a>. </em>When she and co-host Elad Gil first weighed starting a creative collaboration, they explicitly considered devising a project they could commit to consistently shipping ‚Äì even if it wasn‚Äôt perfect.&nbsp;</p><h4><strong>Conviction</strong></h4><blockquote><p><em>No Priors</em> was and still is a side project. Elad and I wanted to do something other than just an investment together, and we settled on a content or network thing. Then the question became: What‚Äôs the right format?&nbsp;</p><p>The theory was that a podcast would be the least amount of work. I think that theory was false, because all things are work.&nbsp;</p><p>Our view was that <strong>we wanted to do something we would enjoy and could maintain</strong>. We knew a lot of people in AI, and it‚Äôs a rapidly evolving sector, and people want to understand what‚Äôs happening. <strong>If all I had to do was talk to someone I thought was actually interesting, and where I might learn something, that felt like something I could do</strong>. We outsourced 99% of it and just made it about having the conversation and our relationship.&nbsp;</p><p><em>‚Äì Sarah Guo</em></p></blockquote><p>As with <em>No Priors</em>, you may quickly find that even your ‚Äúside project‚Äù generates meaningful interest.&nbsp;</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp" width="517" height="517" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1200,&quot;width&quot;:1200,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:517,&quot;bytes&quot;:90664,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/webp&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F809f8ff9-85f9-45d3-9ac5-8ed576c9ce0f_1200x1200.webp 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">Sarah Guo and Elad Gil started the No Priors podcast as a "side project;" It has become influential in AI circles (No Priors)</figcaption></figure></div><p>Thinking in public may appear especially daunting for emerging, unproven managers. <em>Who cares what I, a novice next to the industry‚Äôs luminaries, have to say?</em> Benchmark‚Äôs Sarah Tavel, who began writing her popular blog in 2006 (<a href="https://www.sarahtavel.com/">now a Substack</a>), flipped that framing:&nbsp;</p><h4><strong>Benchmark</strong></h4><blockquote><p>The first posts I wrote were probably in 2006. <strong>The wonderful thing about blogging when you‚Äôre a nobody is that no one cares in the beginning. There‚Äôs no self-consciousness. </strong>Whereas, if you‚Äôre already established when you start blogging, many people can get anxious about it because they want to be good, impressive, or unique.&nbsp;</p><p>By starting when I was young,<strong> I could build this writing muscle</strong>. Over time, I began to realize more and more where my writing had the most resonance.&nbsp;<br><br><em>‚Äì Sarah Tavel</em></p></blockquote><p>If you do not have an existing profile, lean into the freedom such a position affords.</p><p>Keeping your shipping threshold low may not be a practice to hold on to forever. Though it‚Äôs important to getting started, once you have more confidence in your creative abilities and have demonstrated your willingness to ship, you may find it‚Äôs more productive to <em>raise </em>your shipping threshold to maintain a high-quality bar.&nbsp;</p>\n      <p>\n          <a href="https://thegeneralist.substack.com/p/how-vcs-build-soft-power">\n              Read more\n          </a>\n      </p>\n   </body></html>	This is a subscriber-only edition of a premium newsletter designed to help investors, founders, and technologists. 	2024-10-15 13:49:11	2024-10-16 14:47:54.307	2024-10-16 14:52:53.735	{vc}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Feeba0d56-dd9a-4f89-8bd0-4eeb3edc31cd_3543x2757.jpeg	Mario Gabriele	how-vcs-build-soft
172	https://timdenning.substack.com/p/the-internet-will-pay-you-more-for	The Internet Will Pay You More for Your 9-5 Skills than an Employer Ever Will (Few Understand)	Stop stealing from yourself	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg" width="1400" height="873" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:873,&quot;width&quot;:1400,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:337786,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/p/the-internet-will-pay-you-more-for?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/p/the-internet-will-pay-you-more-for?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p><p>Capitalism hides a little-known truth.</p><p>Businesses that hire humans to make money need to pay them the least amount possible. The less they can pay their employees without them leaving, the more money they make.</p><p>This isn‚Äôt an evil conspiracy. It‚Äôs just how the job market works. Once you see this truth you can‚Äôt unsee it.</p><p>Now making money on the internet has become popular in the last few years and created real competition for employers.</p><p>Still, it hasn‚Äôt clicked for most people. Let me explain so you can take advantage of this trend (and still keep your job if you choose).</p><h1><strong>You‚Äôre an accidental entrepreneur and don‚Äôt even realize it (let me show you)</strong></h1><p>An employer doesn‚Äôt pay you for your sexy smile or well-toned ass.</p><p>No. They pay you for a skill stack. Those skills have value. And that value isn‚Äôt unique to your employer. Other people or organizations need those same skills.</p><p>Think of yourself as a business called You INC. Think of your employer as a customer. If you have a traditional full-time job you have one customer.</p><p>I have a friend who owns an IT consulting firm. He told me he has one big government customer. They make him stacks of cash.</p><p>I jokingly said ‚Äúwhat if they terminate you?‚Äù</p><p>His mind seemed to glitch. It‚Äôs obvious that a business with one customer is a stupid idea. So why should our You INC LLC be any different?</p><p>Hint: it shouldn‚Äôt be.</p><p>Every business including the business of You needs more than one customer to diversify and survive.</p><h1><strong>The mental block of ‚Äúsell once‚Äù</strong></h1><p>So if it‚Äôs obvious we need to sell our skills more than once, why do we fall for this trap? Simple.</p><p>Employees (and I was one for decades) are scared of non-compete agreements. These are those hidden paragraphs in an employment contract that are designed to scare you.</p><p>They say things like ‚Äúyou can‚Äôt work for anyone else‚Äù and ‚Äúyou better not steal our company secrets, pal.‚Äù</p><p>These clauses aren‚Äôt serious. Non-compete clauses are hard to enforce.</p><p>I once worked for a company in banking. Their employment contract said that once I work for their banking customer, I couldn‚Äôt work for another global bank for 3 years.</p><p>Lol.</p><p>Okay, so if this company fired me, I couldn‚Äôt get another job for 3 years because they said so? So I‚Äôll just starve and feed my body parts to my daughter for dinner because a corporation said so?</p><p>It‚Äôs crazy when you break it down.</p><p>These clauses are there to make you fearful. No judge in a court is going to say ‚Äúsorry Timbo, you‚Äôre not able to work a job for 3 years. You‚Äôll just have to wait it out. The law is the law.‚Äù</p><p>Now you know why people won‚Äôt have more than one employer (customer). They accidentally think it‚Äôs illegal.</p><p>I got fooled for years until my lawyer told me the truth.</p><h1><strong>The hidden path to sell skills online</strong></h1><p>Many people know they can make money on the internet.</p><p>I run an entire academy on the topic, and the biggest objection I get is ‚Äúwhat do I sell?‚Äù This is where I get confused.</p><p>The thing you sell online is the same thing you already do for work. It‚Äôs the easiest option.</p><p>Instead, I meet nice people who lose their life savings because they think what they sell online has to be different to their current career.</p><p>So they throw themselves into the deep end of a new product or industry they know nothing about and lose the shirt off their back and go broke.</p><p>Sell the thing online that you sell to your employer. Or sell the same or similar product/service as your employer.</p><h1><strong>Internet customers pay more for this bizarre reason</strong></h1><p>I spent my career in finance here in Australia.</p><p>I got paid okay but compared to my American friends I earned peanuts. That‚Äôs because Australia isn‚Äôt as wealthy as America. Our economy is built on top of tourism, college education, and selling coal.</p><p>We‚Äôre a three-trick pony that could easily be blown over by one of our overseas cousins who blows a mouthful of air on us.</p><p>When I started selling my 9-5 skills online the pay went up. That‚Äôs because the people in America who paid me were wealthier. To the finance geeks in the room this is called arbitrage.</p><p>It exists in many countries. The value of your skills in each country has a different price tag.</p><p>You can shop various countries to see which ones pay the most for your skills. Then you can live in that country virtually and get paid for your work through the teleportation device known as the internet.</p><p>This is where people in 3rd world countries ‚Äî who we often feel sorry for ‚Äî have a huge advantage.</p><h1><strong>The big problem is the internet doesn‚Äôt know what skills you have</strong></h1><p>There isn‚Äôt a giant Yellow Pages directory that has the list of every global citizen and the skills they possess.</p><p>LinkedIn has some of the data ‚Ä¶ but it‚Äôs not enough.</p><p>So what happens? Everyday people with great skill sets stay <strong>J</strong>ust <strong>O</strong>ver <strong>B</strong>roke and accept the low pay their current employer offers because they can‚Äôt easily find higher paying employer-customers. Tragic.</p><p>The only solution to the problem is to post content on social media.</p><p>Now some will rebel and say ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt want to be an influencer‚Äù or ‚ÄúI‚Äôm not a content creator.‚Äù</p><p>Yes you are. You have to influence people every day at work to take action in some way. And you‚Äôre a content creator if you sent an email, DM, or text message in the last 365 days.</p><p>Social media is the missing piece of the puzzle.</p><p>When you post online future employers or customers can understand what your skills are. They can then contact you to enquire about your services. This is level one.</p><p>The other option is to build a small library of content online and then message potential customers from that social media account to get new opportunities.</p><p>But without social media content you are a skilled ghost nobody will contact.</p><h1><strong>Top employees are the best kind</strong></h1><p>I‚Äôve worked with multiple high-performers in my career.</p><p>Many of them stay working for the same company for 5+ years. What they forget is if they‚Äôre a high-performing employee they can easily become a high-performing entrepreneur.</p><p>They‚Äôre essentially the same thing.</p><p>Being successful at work means getting results. If you‚Äôve found a way to do it for your current employer, you can probably duplicate the process and do it for a second and third customer. Each will pay you for the privilege.</p><h1><strong>The skill that matters more than business</strong></h1><p>The importance of business skills is overrated in the migration from the one-employer to more-than-one-customer mindset.</p><p>The most important skill is networking.</p><p>Your ability to connect with people and start random conversations determines if you will get exposed to new opportunities.</p><p>And your ability to take social media posts and exploit the credibility they give you to then charge out your skills to new people also matters.</p><p>So if I wanted to find more customers, I‚Äôd master sending kickass DMs/emails that get replies, and producing engaging social media posts.</p><h1><strong>Bringing it all together</strong></h1><p>To progress from one customer to many more takes time.</p><p>There are several paths you can take. I chose to sell my 9-5 skills a second time as a consultant, teacher, and later, coach.</p><p>I never told my employer because it‚Äôs none of their business. And obviously I didn‚Äôt share my employer‚Äôs private information or company secrets.</p><p>But I did share my 9-5 skills like the income pro$titute I am. Because I didn‚Äôt trust any company to resist the temptation to hand out random redundancies whenever they liked.</p><p>Bottom line: sell your skills at least twice. Get paid at least twice. Now money isn‚Äôt such a struggle anymore.</p><p>Tell me which of these ideas you loved the most and why in the comments.</p><div><hr></div><p>I send this email weekly. If you would also like to receive it, join the 129,000+ other smart people who absolutely love it today.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><p>üëâ&nbsp;If you enjoy reading this post, feel free to share it with friends! Or feel free to click the ‚ù§Ô∏è button on this post so more people can discover it on Substack üôè</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/p/the-internet-will-pay-you-more-for?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/p/the-internet-will-pay-you-more-for?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p></body></html>	Capitalism pays employees the least possible. The internet offers opportunities to sell skills for higher pay. Diversify income by selling skills to multiple customers, not just one employer.	2024-10-15 10:11:54	2024-10-16 14:48:58.694	2024-10-16 14:52:53.735	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb9ddb6b1-146c-43fe-a9e1-910dd2bd05d1_1400x873.jpeg	Tim Denning	the-internet-will-pay-you-more-for-your-9-5-skills-than-an-employer-ever-will-few-understand
140	https://grounded.substack.com/p/workforce-wrap-up-september-edition	Workforce Wrap Up: September Edition	Unexpected job growth, a 45,000 dockworker strike, and housing & childcare shortages	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png" width="584" height="307.45636623748214" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:736,&quot;width&quot;:1398,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:584,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><p><em><strong>By: Jomayra Herrera</strong></em></p><p>Welcome to Spooky Season and the start of Q4!&nbsp;</p><p>It‚Äôs time for September‚Äôs workforce wrap up. If you‚Äôre new here, Workforce Wrap Up aims to give a quick 5-minute download of interesting highlights that happened in our labor market / economy in the past month.&nbsp;</p><p>This month, we have some interesting, albeit confusing, data. On one hand, consumer confidence in the labor market has plummeted, there are concerns around an impending childcare cliff and housing shortage, and we had a massive dockworker strike that could‚Äôve been very disruptive. And yet, the labor market surprised us with 254,000 new jobs, stability in layoffs, and an increase in average wages, creating questions about whether the Fed‚Äôs 50 bps rate cut was premature.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>So with that, let‚Äôs dig in.</strong></p><h3><strong>The U.S. crushed expectations, adding 254,000 jobs in September and the unemployment rate fell from 4.2% to 4.1%.&nbsp;</strong></h3><ul><li><p>Forecasts predicted the US only adding 150,000 new jobs last month. Interestingly, <a href="https://www.joinhomebase.com/">Homebase‚Äôs</a> measures were most accurate.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png" width="564" height="345" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:345,&quot;width&quot;:564,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F97c93a78-f62c-4936-96ec-b14d70b3eeac_564x345.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><ul><li><p>Employment in food services and drinking places increased by 69,000, well above the 14,000 average monthly gain over the prior 12 months. Healthcare added 45,000 jobs Large gains were also seen in government, social assistance, and construction.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>Continuing the positive trend, August job growth was revised up by 17,000 and July by 55,000, calling into question the narrative of a cooling labor market.</p></li><li><p>In September, average hourly earnings increased by 13 cents, or 0.4 percent. Over the last 12 months, average hourly earnings increased by 4.0 percent.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>Layoff rates remain low with the average number of workers laid off per month at 1.6 million compared to an average of 1.9 million in 2019.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><blockquote></blockquote><h3><strong>It‚Äôs not all good news though - despite the rapid demand for AI and security-related skills, the unemployment rate for IT professionals increased to 6%</strong></h3><ul><li><p>The IT unemployment rate has been<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/it-unemployment-hits-6-amid-overall-u-s-jobs-growth-bc2f2915"> above the national jobless rate</a> for seven of the last eight months.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>Reductions in IT are concentrated in traditional technology roles like managing back-end corporate systems.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>According to Indeed, software development IT support job postings are about 30% fewer than they were before the pandemic.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>This is driving a massive consumer demand to develop critical AI, security, and cloud-related skills.</p></li></ul><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png" width="352" height="439.21194029850744" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:836,&quot;width&quot;:670,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:352,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6673a257-84d9-431e-ab9a-cf574368f802_670x836.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><h3><strong>ICYMI 45,000 workers at the 14 ports on the Atlantic and Gulf coasts went on strike last week</strong></h3><ul><li><p>The strike was largely about disagreements related to wages and automation. On the former, employers agreed to a 62% raise over six years which helped to bring workers back. Their master agreement is now extended to January 15, 2025.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>Automation is more tricky as the union has already agreed to some degree of semi-automation in prior contracts. This is a reminder that while a lot of the conversation is around AI coming to replace knowledge workers, there continue to be concerns about automation at the frontline.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>Thankfully the strike only lasted three days. Economists estimated that if the strike continued it would cost about $4.3B per week in lost exports and imports, which could have reduced Q4 GDP growth by half a percentage point.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>While many retailers stocked up on inventory in advance to avoid any potential disruptions, food and beverage stores were an outlier. There were concerns around potential rises in food if the strikes were to continue.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png" width="490" height="356.20567375886526" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:410,&quot;width&quot;:564,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:490,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1ce005ec-df1e-45e2-94e1-943878d4be03_564x410.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><h3><strong>Consumer confidence declined by the most in three years in September, as Americans are increasingly concerned about the labor market</strong></h3><ul><li><p>Consumers are increasingly pessimistic about the economy, largely because of concerns related to employment.</p></li><li><p>Only 31% of consumers said jobs were plentiful, down 2 points from August, and the share of those who said jobs were ‚Äúhard to get‚Äù increased 1.5 percentage points to 18.3%.</p></li><li><p>The conference board shared that concerns around inflation are starting to decline, especially relative to employment.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png" width="356" height="608.4822695035461" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/bdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:964,&quot;width&quot;:564,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:356,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fbdc2e71d-79ec-4ea7-b0be-01e1a92f0e13_564x964.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><h3><strong>A new <a href="https://tcf.org/content/report/child-care-funding-cliff-at-one-year/">report on the state of childcare</a> was released - while the ‚Äúchild care cliff‚Äù is less dire than initially predicted, there are still clear signs of increased costs of care, labor shortages, and closure of sites.&nbsp;</strong></h3><ul><li><p>Child care prices are increasing faster than overall inflation. In fact, nationally child care prices are 20% higher than they were in 2019.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png" width="468" height="459.8961038961039" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1362,&quot;width&quot;:1386,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:468,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe6d6d303-01b9-4922-90f1-776d0eb6a313_1386x1362.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><ul><li><p>In forty-five states plus D.C., the average annual price of child care for two children in a center exceeded annual mortgage payments and, in <a href="https://www.childcareaware.org/thechildcarestandstill/#PriceofCare">all fifty states plus D.C., it exceeded average annual rent payments</a>.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>The childcare challenge is worse for lower income families. A <a href="https://link.axios.com/click/36860980.">report by the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago </a>found that in 2021 families below the poverty line spent 27% of their income on care, up from 23% in 2019. Whereas higher income families spent 7% of their income on care in 2021, a decline from 8% in 2019.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>There has been a 12 percent decline in licensed family child care homes since 2019, and a small 1.3 percent increase in child care centers.</p></li><li><p>In the five states the report focused on, licensed child care programs have either declined or flattened since 2019.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png" width="512" height="526.1940594059406" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1038,&quot;width&quot;:1010,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:512,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa62d7b80-b994-4853-b989-52491324871d_1010x1038.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><ul><li><p>In positive news - between 2021 and 2023, eleven states and Washington D.C. spent their own state budget dollars to help stabilize child care. The National Women‚Äôs Law Center found that women in those states who had children under the age of 12  and wanted to work but reported not working because of childcare issues<a href="https://nwlc.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/Pluse-4.0-Child-Care-Fact-Sheet-May-2024-2.pdf"> decreased by 13 percentage point</a>s between fall 2023 and spring 2024.&nbsp;</p></li></ul><blockquote></blockquote><h3><strong>And lastly, the US is facing a severe housing shortage, which is concerning if rates continue to decline and demand for housing spikes.&nbsp;</strong></h3><ul><li><p>In 2005, builders were constructing new homes at a rate of about 2.2 million per year. Now, the number is 1.2 million.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>The current housing shortage can be traced back to the 2008 housing crisis when many home builders went out of business and the industry did not recover.&nbsp;</p></li><li><p>If rates continue to decline and demand spikes, there is not enough supply to meet that demand which will likely only worsen housing affordability issues.</p></li></ul><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png" width="400" height="290.6666666666667" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/caf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:872,&quot;width&quot;:1200,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:400,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcaf8f379-e6c2-4788-960e-14c48d5ab1bb_1200x872.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a></figure></div><p>The next Workforce Wrap Up will be a big one - we will have a newly elected president, data on whether the September job uptick was a blip or indicative of a rebound in the market, and whether the Fed will continue cutting rates.&nbsp;</p><p>Until then, if you ever want to nerd out on any of this shoot me an email at jomayra@reachcapital.com!</p><p></p></body></html>	The U.S. added 254,000 jobs in September, exceeding expectations, but the IT unemployment rate increased to 6%. A dockworker strike was resolved, and consumer confidence declined due to concerns about the labor market.	2024-10-08 13:03:23	2024-10-14 08:17:26.908	2024-10-14 08:36:19.286	{vc}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F990e67e4-f5aa-4403-bf7d-b2cb7971fe41_1398x736.png	Grounded	workforce-wrap-up-september
165	https://www.eu.vc/p/venture-debt-structuring-and-deal	Venture Debt: Structuring & Deal Terms	Watch now | with Hemal Fraser-Rawal, General Partner @ White Star Capital	<html><head></head><body><p>Would you like to get early access to the next live masterclass on this topic?</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://airtable.com/app3F8k6EuPFgP51d/pagQj8JhHnsV1VJnz/form&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Register Here&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://airtable.com/app3F8k6EuPFgP51d/pagQj8JhHnsV1VJnz/form"><span>Register Here</span></a></p><div><hr></div><p>‚ÄãThis masterclass covers essential aspects of venture debt, from its origins and rationale to detailed explorations of deal terms and geographic variations. Designed with GPs in mind, we offer practical insights and strategies to enhance your understanding and application of venture debt in your portfolio management.</p><div><hr></div><h2>Resources</h2><p>Access the resources crafted for this sessions specifically.</p>\n      <p>\n          <a href="https://www.eu.vc/p/venture-debt-structuring-and-deal">\n              Read more\n          </a>\n      </p>\n   </body></html>	Get early access to the next live masterclass on venture debt.	2024-10-16 06:31:02	2024-10-16 14:47:25.957	2024-10-16 14:52:53.735	{vc}	https://api.substack.com/feed/podcast/150103156/4d977de322ef8a5b4179f18bf0d82302.mp3	David Cruz e Silva üéô	venture-debt-structuring-and
150	https://www.eu.vc/p/the-power-of-experience-nicola-mcclaffertys	The Power of Experience: Nicola McClafferty‚Äôs Journey from Investor to Founder and Back as a Series A+ Investor	An insightful discussion on the state of European entrepreneurship and how current market conditions create opportunities for strong businesses.	<html><head></head><body><p>Welcome to a new episode of our special series, <strong>At The Cap Table Series, </strong>on EUVC<strong>.</strong></p><p>Today,<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/antleri/"> Sarah Finegan</a>, Senior Investor at<a href="https://www.antler.co/"> Antler</a> has a discussion with<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/nicolamcclafferty/"> Nicola McClafferty</a>, Partner at<a href="https://www.moltenventures.com/"> Molten Ventures</a>. Molten Ventures, formerly Draper Esprit, is a venture capital firm investing in high-growth technology companies with global ambitions, with offices in London and Dublin. Molten is publicly listed on the<a href="https://www.eu.vc/p/euvc-176-rewriting-how-private-markets?utm_source=publication-search"> London Stock Exchange</a> and takes flexible and patient capital to invest across primary, secondary, and fund funds. Molten invests ~$200 million a year across Seed - Series B stage companies with ~$2 billion AUM.</p><p>Nicola spent 5 years as a venture capital investor with<a href="https://www.eu.vc/p/act-180-rana-yared-gp-at-balderton?utm_source=publication-search"> Balderton Capital</a> and media consultancy<a href="https://www.ravensbeck.com/"> Ravensbeck</a>, focusing on early-stage technology and digital consumer investments. She graduated from University College Dublin with a degree in International Business and French.</p><p>In this episode, Nicola shares her personal journey, including her transition from VC to founder and back again, and how that experience shapes her approach as a leading venture capitalist today. She discusses her experiences as a founder, including scaling companies from zero to one and through later stages.&nbsp;</p><p>We‚Äôll explore Molten Ventures‚Äô unique model, which encompasses everything from Fund of Funds investments to secondaries and Series A-C funding, as well as the current state of entrepreneurship in Europe and beyond.&nbsp;</p><p>The episode also covers trends in consumer software, vertical SaaS, and B2B2C, along with Nicola‚Äôs insights on the future of marketplaces and e-commerce. To wrap things up, we‚Äôll have some fun with rapid-fire questions, gaining personal insights from Nicola, including her advice to her younger self.</p><p>So, whether you're a founder, an investor, or just fascinated by the tech ecosystem, stay tuned for an engaging and insightful conversation. Let's get started!</p><p><em>Watch it here or add it to your episodes on <a href="https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/euvc/id1544598239">Apple </a>or <a href="https://open.spotify.com/show/0WO5adjTSnzxCC3l2sRq1f">Spotify</a> üéß chapters for easy navigation available on the Spotify/Apple episode.</em></p><iframe class="spotify-wrap podcast" data-attrs="{&quot;image&quot;:&quot;https://i.scdn.co/image/ab6765630000ba8a3b32df460bb7743b9157b79d&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;EUVC&quot;,&quot;subtitle&quot;:&quot;The European VC&quot;,&quot;description&quot;:&quot;Podcast&quot;,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://open.spotify.com/show/0WO5adjTSnzxCC3l2sRq1f&quot;,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;noScroll&quot;:false}" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/show/0WO5adjTSnzxCC3l2sRq1f" frameborder="0" gesture="media" allowfullscreen="true" allow="encrypted-media" loading="lazy" data-component-name="Spotify2ToDOM"></iframe><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd7ca142d-62d2-4955-b9b4-e6cb7fc0e5c3_750x40.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM">